testis is nearly twice the size of the left testis and is tender to palpation. Future investigations confirm that this is a tumour and a right orchidectomy is performed. Histological examination reveals a haemorrhagic tumour with areas of necrosis. Microscopy shows sheets of undifferentiated cells with primitive gland-like structures.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Choriocarcinoma","Embryonal carcinoma","Seminoma","Teratoma","Yolk sac tumour"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEmbryonal carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by sheets of poorly differentiated cells with primitive gland-like structures, often presenting as a painful, haemorrhagic mass with areas of necrosis. It typically affects young adult men.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EYolk sac tumours\u003C/strong\u003E typically show Schiller-Duval bodies and are more common in children. \u003Cstrong\u003EChoriocarcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E shows both syncytiotrophoblasts and cytotrophoblasts on histology. \u003Cstrong\u003ETeratoma\u003C/strong\u003E contains tissue from all three germ cell layers and shows well-differentiated structures. \u003Cstrong\u003ESeminoma\u003C/strong\u003E shows uniform cells with clear cytoplasm and distinct cell borders arranged in sheets with lymphocytic infiltration.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Embryonal carcinoma shows sheets of undifferentiated cells and primitive gland-like structures on histology.","Embryonal carcinoma is a malignant testicular germ cell tumour that typically presents with a painful, haemorrhagic mass."],"references":["Boccellino M, Vanacore D, Zappavigna S, Cavaliere C, Rossetti S, D\u0027Aniello C, Chieffi P, Amler E, Buonerba C, Di Lorenzo G, Di Franco R, Izzo A, Piscitelli R, Iovane G, Muto P, Botti G, Perdon\u00e0 S, Caraglia M, Facchini G. Testicular cancer from diagnosis to epigenetic factors. Oncotarget. 2017 Sep 18;8(61):104654-104663. doi: 10.18632/oncotarget.20992. PMID: 29262668; PMCID: PMC5732834","Chung P, Warde P. Testicular cancer: germ cell tumours. BMJ Clin Evid. 2016 Jan 7;2016:1807. PMID: 26741128; PMCID: PMC4704678","Cheng L, Albers P, Berney DM, Feldman DR, Daugaard G, Gilligan T, Looijenga LHJ. Testicular cancer. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2018 Oct 5;4(1):29. doi: 10.1038/s41572-018-0029-0. PMID: 30291251","Ansell, I. D. (2012). Atlas of male reproductive pathology (Vol. 10). Springer Science \u0026 Business Media","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50127"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15878"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50127","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50127"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-24T15:36:13+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-24T15:36:39+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8569"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64693"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemC